PROMPT list_append_extend_comparison
WITH BUDGET 6000 tokens
USING MODEL "claude-sonnet-4-5"

SELECT
    system_role("You are a Python expert specializing in list operations, data structures, and Python's built-in methods with deep knowledge of how list modification methods work internally and their practical applications.")

GENERATE
    compare_list_methods("Explain the fundamental differences between list.append() and list.extend() methods in Python, covering: the definition of list.append() as a method that adds a single element to the end of the list, treating whatever is passed as one item regardless of its type, versus list.extend() as a method that adds all elements from an iterable to the end of the list individually, the behavior differences where append() adds exactly one item to the list even if that item is itself a list or other collection, while extend() iterates through the argument and adds each element separately, concrete examples showing how [1, 2, 3].append([4, 5]) results in [1, 2, 3, [4, 5]] with the nested list as a single element, while [1, 2, 3].extend([4, 5]) results in [1, 2, 3, 4, 5] with individual elements added, the parameter requirements where append() takes exactly one argument of any type, while extend() takes one argument that must be iterable such as lists, tuples, strings, or other sequences, performance characteristics where both methods modify the original list in-place and return None, with append() being O(1) amortized time complexity for adding one element, while extend() is O(k) where k is the number of elements in the iterable being added, practical use cases including append() for adding single items like numbers, strings, or objects including nested data structures, while extend() is used for combining lists, adding multiple elements at once, or flattening one level of nesting, the equivalent operations showing how my_list.append(item) is equivalent to my_list[len(my_list):] = [item], while my_list.extend(iterable) is equivalent to my_list[len(my_list):] = iterable, common mistakes including using append() when extend() is intended, which creates unwanted nesting, or passing a single non-iterable to extend() which raises a TypeError, the relationship to other list methods where both are in-place modifications unlike concatenation with + operator which creates new lists, and best practices for choosing between append() for single item addition and extend() for adding multiple items from iterables.")
WITH OUTPUT BUDGET 3000 tokens, TEMPERATURE 0.2, FORMAT markdown;